Sharvari (@sharvari) loves her heritage and dreams of wearing a traditional Nauvari sari on her wedding day. Her most precious heirloom? A collection of Paithani saris passed down through generations. Watch our August digital cover star as she recalls reading Vogue for the first time at a salon with her mother and sister.

Ambition in Sharvari's world shifts, expands and sometimes sits in the discomfort just to see what might grow there. “I think ultimately, my ambition is to go to bed each night feeling like I did my best. Whether that’s in work, in relationships, in eating right or being kind; that, to me, is a successful day,” says our August digital cover star.

Fame reflects and distorts. But Sharvari is wary of mistaking perception for identity. “If I wake up feeling low, I acknowledge it… I don’t always need to feel gorgeous or confident every single day.” At the link in bio, she speaks about grace, ambition and holding on to herself.

No film school fable or tortured backstory. Just Aishwarya Rai Bachchan in Dhoom 2 and a gut feeling. “She was so cool, so powerful. She made me want to dress up and act,” says Sharvari. Years later, our August digital cover star was assisting on the sets of Pyaar Ka Punchnama 2, she realised “I loved being on set, but I knew I wanted to try acting. Something in me said, ‘This is what I want to do’”.

“I’m very expressive. I cry a lot. I laugh a lot. I wear my emotions on my sleeve. I feel things deeply, and I don’t think that’s a bad thing,” she states plainly. As she talks about her grandmother’s chaat parties, late-night drives with friends and home-cooked meals, you wonder Is it just “packaged for relatability” spin? Not when you’re sitting across from her. Sharvari, it seems, wants to be known.
